We welcome members of the public to virtually attend the Board Meeting tomorrow night, July 21, 2020 starting at 6 pm, due to the newest Governor’s Executive Order limiting in-door gatherings to no more than 25 people. The Zoom link is available below and on the District website.

While Zoom may only accomodate 100 attendees, a separate YouTube stream will also be provided to ensure ALL who'd like to attend virtually, may do so. That YouTube link will be disseminated shortly before the meeting.

You may submit questions ahead of time to Business Manager, Derrek Fink at dfink@miltonsd.org. Please understand we have considered many of the questions you may have and will be doing our best to address them during the meeting.

Meeting Link: https://zoom.us/j/96737317356
Agenda Link: https://app.agendamanager.com/miltonasd/meeting/view/40773/

post_text:
Seniors!!!

We’re doing this, the Drive-Thru Graduation Ceremony “Ride Into Your Future” is happening tonight. We want to do what we can to avoid any bad weather, so we’re moving the Virtual Graduation Ceremony premiere on Facebook to 4:00pm, and you should report directly to the Turkey Hill entrance at 5:00pm and we will begin the ceremony at that time. Please spread the word to any family and friends who will be watching the live stream that they should tune into Facebook as soon as the Virtual Graduation Ceremony is over, we will start it as soon as the first car reaches the starting line.

4:00pm – Virtual Graduation Ceremony posted to Facebook (it is pre-recorded, so it can be watched at any time)
5:00pm – Seniors report to the Turkey Hill entrance. Drive-Thru Graduation begins ASAP after that.

We cannot wait to see all of you and celebrate your success. Don’t forget to wear your Cap and Gown!!! See you soon!

Mr. Rantz

post_text: MASD Senior, Mylea Neidig, had the idea of having herself and some of her 2020 classmates to record themselves reading their favorite books from their youth, and then share them with MASD students in grades K-2. Dr. Kirkpatrick, Director of Education, supported the initiative by purchasing one book for each of the K-2 classrooms. Then these books – ones like Oh, the Places You Will Go and Where the Wild Things Are – were placed in the hands of the seniors! These videos are now online for our young students to watch at home, or during their online classes with their teachers. The books are then dedicated to these classrooms, where they will be enjoyed for years to come! Inside each cover is also a specially designed dedication sticker designed by Nina Willow. Way to go Mylea and the seniors of the National Honor Society and Leadership Team! #SeniorCelebration #PantherPride
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Mylea Neidig Reads Where the Wild Things Are
text:
MASD Senior, Mylea Neidig, had the idea of having herself and some of her 2020 classmates to record themselves reading their favorite books from their youth, and then share them with MASD students in grades K-2. Dr. Kirkpatrick, Director of Education, supported the initiative by purchasing one book for each of the K-2 classrooms. Then these books – ones like Oh, the Places You Will Go and Where the Wild Things Are – were placed in the hands of the seniors! These videos are now online for our young students to watch at home, or during their online classes with their teachers. The books are then dedicated to these classrooms, where they will be enjoyed for years to come! Inside each cover is also a specially designed dedication sticker designed by Nina Willow. Way to go Mylea and the seniors of the National Honor Society and Leadership Team! #SeniorCelebration #PantherPride

post_text:
Congratulations to Addison Zettlemoyer for winning Milton Middle School's Stock Game!

Addison had the highest portfolio for Milton Middle School, with a total portfolio value of $110,247.85

Each student starts with $100,000 of imaginary funds and has ten weeks to grow it's value based on the real stock market results. This was by far the most challenging year with the last four weeks of the game being played at home and little interaction with the instructor.

And beside playing from home the market did not behave as usual due to Covid19 ... most strategies went out the window!

For Addison to net $10,247.85 in ten weeks is outstanding.

She placed 22nd out of 607 students that actually made trades in the game.

Based on how the Daily Item and PennCFL make the ranking, Addison put MMS in fourth place, qualifying her for a prize!

Again well done Addison!

#InvestingInOurFuture #PantherPride

Sharing some love this afternoon, from the teachers and administrators who supported a kindness campaign for many of the first responders in our community!

Donations were collected to purchase some sweet treats and surprises!

Candy bars and treats from Gable House Bakery went to Evangelical Hospital, sandwiches from The Breaking Bread Company to the State Police barracks at Milton, Gift Cards from Lisa's Milltown Deli to the Milton Police Department and more than 100 candy bars to the employees at our local Weis Markets.

From all of us at the Milton Area School District, THANK YOU, to those on the front line, making a difference!

We want to take a moment and thank our students, teachers and parents for staying positive this week while we work through some connectivity issues! Thankfully, each day it's improving.

However, there are some in our district who struggle to receive reliable, high speed internet because of our rural landscape. Our Superintendent, Dr. Cathy Keegan, is calling on state lawmakers to end a drought of poor internet service in rural Pennsylvania.

Our district was featured by WHYY - as they report on the struggles every rural district in our Commonwealth now faces.

post_text:
Good news!

With students at home now in an eLearning environment, Service Electric Cablevision (SECV) will offer 90 days free Internet service to students and professors/teachers who do not already subscribe to SECV Internet. This offer includes the 40M x 4M tier of Internet service, along with a free cable modem rental. It applies only to new customers that have not subscribed to SECV Internet service within the last sixty (60) days and other restrictions may apply. Self-installation is required with the assistance of a technician outside the residence to ensure the safety of our employees. All new customers must provide written proof of their child’s current enrollment at a local school in SECV’s service area. All teachers must reside in SECV’s service area and provide evidence of current employment status. For more information or to enroll in the eLearning offer, please have students or teachers call Service Electric at 877.955.7328.

Happy Milton Monday!
We are aware that we are experiencing some technological issues. Together we are facing a brand new virtual world and we anticipated that the first few days would require all of us to work collaboratively through challenges. Your enthusiasm for learning and your wish to reconnect with our teachers is infectious. Thank you for your patience and understanding!
text:
Happy Milton Monday!
We are aware that we are experiencing some technological issues. Together we are facing a brand new virtual world and we anticipated that the first few days would require all of us to work collaboratively through challenges. Your enthusiasm for learning and your wish to reconnect with our teachers is infectious. Thank you for your patience and understanding!

post_text: Check out this special Spanish message from Mrs. Hunter!
text: Check out this special Spanish message from Mrs. Hunter!

post_text:
Tomorrow, together we will embark on a brand new learning environment. What we know as normal will no longer be true but it’s OK. We are ok. We are resilient. We are strong. We possess grit. We believe in the importance of learning and we are willing to take risks along with you.

We know you have fears. We are afraid, too. We all understand and empathize with you. There is so much unknown and uncertainty. With virtual learning, comes new etiquette. As virtual learners, our students must have PRIDE and be polite, respectful, inspiring, disciplined and encouraging. We will reinforce this need for etiquette through an easy to remember slogan. Along with you, we will do our best to uphold the expectations of our Milton virtual learning community.

As virtual learners, our students must have PRIDE and be polite, respectful, inspiring, disciplined and encouraging. We will reinforce this need for etiquette through an easy to remember slogan. Along with you, we will do our best to uphold the expectations of our Milton virtual learning community.

post_text: The CSIU will be hosting a music event this afternoon. Please check out the link if you are interested in your children participating.
shared_text:
CSIU / Central Susquehanna Intermediate Unit / IU 16
March 19 at 11:00 AM ·

REMINDER: Today at 1 and 2 p.m. 🥁🎼🎹🎷🎸🎤

The Central Susquehanna Intermediate Unit (CSIU) announces it will livestream a music program on March 19 at 1 and 2 p.m.

Join us at 1 p.m. as we livestream a music program geared toward preschool and elementary school aged children.

A program at 2 p.m. will also be live-streamed and geared toward our more mature learners.

Tune in to the programs at: www.csiu.org/music
Forward the link to anyone who may be interested in an hour of uplifting music.

We will also be streaming on Facebook Live!

Milton Area School District received a visit from Penn State PROWellness Healthy Champion representatives today who distributed watermelon seeds to all the students at White Deer Elementary. Featured in the cafeteria getting their seeds is Mrs. Howers’ second grade class. Students celebrated Going for the Greens, a PROWellness program highlighting the importance of incorporating a variety of fruits and vegetables every day, especially the GREENS. Today’s menu featured fresh broccoli with dip and spinach salad. All four schools in the district are Healthy Champion certified!
#InvestingInOurFuture #PantherPride

post_text:
Ariane Raymond and Timothy Marvin’s business plan, TERGEO, has won honors to compete at the Future Business Leaders of America State Leadership Conference and PennCFL Entrepreneurship Championship.
The TERGEO business plan was among only ten high school business plans from across the state of Pennsylvania to qualify for the final round of competition at FBLA states. Ariane and Timothy will present their business plan to a panel of judges during the FBLA State Leadership Conference April 5-8 in Hershey, PA.
As a PennCFL Entrepreneurship regional winner, Ariane and Timothy were awarded a $100 prize as well as the opportunity to be judged in the PennCFL Entrepreneurship State Championship at PSU Innovation Park in April.
Panther Proud of Timothy and Ariane!
